=== n=5: exhaustive check ===
  Ω is ALWAYS complete at n=5 ✓

=== n=6: exhaustive check ===
  NOT complete! bits=80, H=27, cycles=11, non-adj=1
    Disjoint: {0, 4, 5} ⊥ {1, 2, 3}
  NOT complete! bits=81, H=23, cycles=9, non-adj=1
    Disjoint: {0, 4, 5} ⊥ {1, 2, 3}
  NOT complete! bits=82, H=23, cycles=9, non-adj=1
    Disjoint: {0, 4, 5} ⊥ {1, 2, 3}

  NOT complete: 15440/32768 tournaments

=== n=7: sampling ===
  trial=0: H=159, disjoint 3-cycles: {1, 3, 5} ⊥ {0, 2, 4}
  trial=1: H=171, disjoint 3-cycles: {1, 3, 5} ⊥ {0, 2, 4}
  trial=2: H=95, disjoint 3-cycles: {2, 4, 6} ⊥ {0, 1, 3}
  Non-complete (has disjoint 3-cycles): 8670/10000
  First n where Ω can be non-complete: n=7 (3+3+1 = 7 vertices)
  This is WHY α₂ > 0 is first possible at n ≥ 7 for 3-cycles
  (but at n=6, disjoint 3-cycles need 3+3=6 vertices, so barely possible)
